\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"SessionStart\",\"hookName\":\"SessionStart:clear\",\"command\":\"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/hooks-handlers/session-start.sh\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"55dccdc1-89f0-4695-af6f-745fd844f250\",\"toolUseID\":\"55dccdc1-89f0-4695-af6f-745fd844f250\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T19:38:12.963Z\",\"uuid\":\"174b9db8-c52c-46bb-a534-4c440cacdd32\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"174b9db8-c52c-46bb-a534-4c440cacdd32\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"a3480680-037a-4f32-90f3-99642180a443\",\"version\":\"2.1.70\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"sequential-stargazing-twilight\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Implement the following plan:\\n\\n# E2E Triage Automation — Implementation Plan\\n\\n## Context\\n\\nE2E tests on `main` are flaky and constantly changing. When they fail in CI, someone has to manually download artifacts, analyze them, figure out if it's a real bug or agent non-determinism, and then either fix the test or file a bug. This plan automates that entire workflow with a new `/e2e-triage` skill backed by a reusable artifact download script.\\n\\n**Outcome**: E2E failures on `main` auto-trigger Claude Code (Opus) in CI via `workflow_run`. Claude downloads artifacts, analyzes failures, classifies flaky vs real bug, and creates a batched PR (flaky) or GitHub issue with dedup (real bug). Also available locally via `/e2e-triage`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## New Files\\n\\n### 1. `scripts/download-e2e-artifacts.sh`\\n\\nReusable shell script for downloading E2E artifacts from GitHub Actions.\\n\\n**Interface:**\\n```\\nUsage: scripts/download-e2e-artifacts.sh [RUN_ID | RUN_URL | \\\"latest\\\"]\\n  - RUN_ID:  numeric GitHub Actions run ID\\n  - RUN_URL: full URL like https://github.com/entireio/cli/actions/runs/12345\\n  - \\\"latest\\\": most recent failed E2E run on main\\n```\\n\\n**Behavior:**\\n- Requires `gh` CLI installed and authenticated (validates upfront)\\n- For `latest`: `gh run list -w e2e.yml --status=failure -L1 --json databaseId -q '.[0].databaseId'`\\n- Extracts run ID from URL via regex if URL provided\\n- Downloads to `e2e/artifacts/ci-<run-id>/` using `gh run download <run-id> --dir <dest>`\\n- Restructures: moves `e2e-artifacts-<agent>/*` → `<dest>/<agent>/` (flattens wrapper dirs)\\n- Writes `.run-info.json` with `run_id`, `run_url`, `commit`, `downloaded_at`\\n- Prints absolute path of download directory as **last line** of stdout (for callers to capture)\\n- Prints metadata (run ID, agents found, commit) to stderr\\n- Exits non-zero with clear message if: `gh` missing, not authenticated, run not found, artifacts expired\\n\\n**Key details:**\\n- Get run URL: `gh run view <run-id> --json url -q '.url'`\\n- Get commit: `gh run view <run-id> --json headSha -q '.headSha'`\\n- List downloaded artifact dirs: `ls -d e2e-artifacts-*/`\\n- Add to `.gitignore`: `e2e/artifacts/ci-*/` (if not already covered by `e2e/artifacts/`)\\n\\n### 2. `.claude/skills/e2e-triage/SKILL.md`\\n\\nThe main skill orchestrating the full workflow.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Skill Workflow (7 Steps)\\n\\n### Step 1: Download Artifacts\\n\\n**If given a run ID, URL, or \\\"latest\\\":**\\n```bash\\nartifact_dir=$(scripts/download-e2e-artifacts.sh <input>)\\n```\\n\\n**If given a local path:** Use directly, skip download.\\n\\n### Step 2: Identify Failures\\n\\nFor each agent subdirectory in artifact root:\\n1. Read `report.nocolor.txt` → list failed tests with error messages, file:line refs\\n2. Skip agents with zero failures\\n3. Build failure list: `[(test_name, agent, error_line, duration, file:line)]`\\n\\n### Step 3: Analyze Each Failure (debug-e2e methodology)\\n\\nFor each failure:\\n1. Read `console.log` — what did the agent actually do?\\n2. Read test source at `file:line` — what was expected?\\n3. Read `entire-logs/entire.log` — any CLI errors, panics, unexpected behavior?\\n4. Read `git-log.txt` / `git-tree.txt` — repo state\\n5. Read `checkpoint-metadata/` — corrupt or missing metadata?\\n\\n### Step 4: Classify Each Failure\\n\\n**Strong `real-bug` signals (any one sufficient):**\\n- `entire.log` contains `\\\"level\\\":\\\"ERROR\\\"` or panic/stack traces\\n- Checkpoint metadata structurally corrupt (malformed JSON, missing `checkpoint_id`/`strategy`)\\n- Session state file missing or malformed when expected\\n- Hooks did not fire at all (no `hook invoked` log entries)\\n- Shadow/metadata branch has wrong tree structure\\n- Same test fails across 3+ agents with same non-timeout symptom\\n- Error references CLI code (panic in `cmd/entire/cli/`)\\n\\n**Strong `flaky` signals (unless overridden by real-bug):**\\n- `signal: killed` (timeout)\\n- `context deadline exceeded` or `WaitForCheckpoint.*exceeded deadline`\\n- Agent asked for confirmation instead of acting\\n- Agent created file at wrong path / wrong name\\n- Agent produced no output\\n- Agent committed when it shouldn't have (or vice versa)\\n- Test fails for only one agent, passes for others\\n- Duration near timeout limit\\n\\n**Ambiguous:** Read `entire.log` carefully — if hooks fired correctly and metadata is valid → lean `flaky`. If hooks fired but produced wrong results → lean `real-bug`.\\n\\n### Step 5: Cross-Agent Correlation\\n\\nBefore acting:\\n- Same test fails 3+ agents with similar errors → override to `real-bug`\\n- Same test fails only 1 agent → lean `flaky`\\n\\n### Step 6: Take Action\\n\\n#### For `flaky` failures → Batched PR\\n\\n1. Create branch `fix/e2e-flaky-<run-id>`\\n2. Apply fixes to ALL flaky test files (one branch, one PR):\\n   - Agent asked for confirmation → append \\\"Do not ask for confirmation\\\" to prompt\\n   - Agent wrote to wrong path → be more explicit about paths\\n   - Agent committed when shouldn't → add \\\"Do not commit\\\"\\n   - Checkpoint wait timeout → increase timeout argument\\n   - Agent timeout (signal: killed) → increase per-test timeout, simplify prompt\\n3. Run verification:\\n   ```bash\\n   mise run test:e2e:canary   # Must pass\\n   mise run fmt && mise run lint\\n   ```\\n4. If canary fails → investigate and adjust; if unfixable, fall back to issue creation\\n5. Commit and create PR:\\n   ```bash\\n   gh pr create \\\\\\n     --title \\\"fix(e2e): make flaky tests more resilient (run <run-id>)\\\" \\\\\\n     --body \\\"<structured body with per-test changes, evidence, run link>\\\"\\n   ```\\n\\n#### For `real-bug` failures → Issue (with dedup)\\n\\n1. **Search existing issues first:**\\n   ```bash\\n   gh issue list --search \\\"is:open label:e2e <TestName>\\\" --json number,title,url\\n   ```\\n2. **If matching issue exists:** Add a comment with new evidence:\\n   ```bash\\n   gh issue comment <number> --body \\\"<verification details, run link, new evidence>\\\"\\n   ```\\n   Comment should note \\\"Verified still failing in CI run <URL>\\\" plus any new diagnostic details.\\n\\n3. **If no matching issue:** Create new:\\n   ```bash\\n   gh issue create \\\\\\n     --title \\\"E2E: <TestName> fails — <brief symptom>\\\" \\\\\\n     --label \\\"bug,e2e\\\" \\\\\\n     --body \\\"<structured body>\\\"\\n   ```\\n\\n   Issue body includes:\\n   - Test name, agent(s), CI run link, frequency\\n   - Failure summary (expected vs actual)\\n   - Root cause analysis (which CLI component: hooks, session, checkpoint, attribution, strategy)\\n   - Key evidence: `entire.log` excerpts, `console.log` excerpts, git state\\n   - Reproduction steps\\n   - Suspected fix location (file, function, reason)\\n\\n### Step 7: Summary Report\\n\\nPrint a table:\\n```\\n| Test | Agent(s) | Classification | Action | Link |\\n|------|----------|---------------|--------|------|\\n| TestFoo | claude-code | flaky | PR #123 | url |\\n| TestBar | all agents | real-bug | Issue #456 (existing, commented) | url |\\n| TestBaz | opencode | real-bug | Issue #457 (new) | url |\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n---\\n\\n## CI Automation: `.github/workflows/e2e-triage.yml`\\n\\nA new workflow that auto-runs Claude Code on E2E failure.\\n\\n### Trigger\\n\\n```yaml\\non:\\n  workflow_run:\\n    workflows: [\\\"E2E Tests\\\"]\\n    types: [completed]\\n```\\n\\nThe `workflow_run` event fires after the E2E workflow finishes. The job only runs when the conclusion is `failure`.\\n\\n### Workflow Structure\\n\\n```yaml\\nname: E2E Triage\\n\\non:\\n  workflow_run:\\n    workflows: [\\\"E2E Tests\\\"]\\n    types: [completed]\\n\\npermissions:\\n  contents: write      # Create branches and push fixes\\n  pull-requests: write # Create PRs\\n  issues: write        # Create/comment on issues\\n  actions: read        # Download artifacts\\n\\njobs:\\n  triage:\\n    if: ${{ github.event.workflow_run.conclusion == 'failure' }}\\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\\n    timeout-minutes: 30\\n    steps:\\n      - name: Checkout repository\\n        uses: actions/checkout@v6\\n\\n      - name: Setup mise\\n        uses: jdx/mise-action@v3\\n\\n      - name: Install system dependencies\\n        run: sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get install -y tmux\\n\\n      - name: Install Claude Code CLI\\n        run: curl -fsSL https://claude.ai/install.sh | bash\\n\\n      - name: Download E2E artifacts\\n        run: |\\n          scripts/download-e2e-artifacts.sh ${{ github.event.workflow_run.id }}\\n\\n      - name: Run triage\\n        env:\\n          ANTHROPIC_API_KEY: ${{ secrets.ANTHROPIC_API_KEY }}\\n          GH_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}\\n        run: |\\n          RUN_ID=\\\"${{ github.event.workflow_run.id }}\\\"\\n          ARTIFACT_DIR=\\\"e2e/artifacts/ci-${RUN_ID}\\\"\\n          claude -p \\\\\\n            --model claude-opus-4-6 \\\\\\n            --allowedTools \\\"Bash(mise run *),Bash(gh *),Bash(git *),Read,Write,Edit,Glob,Grep\\\" \\\\\\n            \\\"You are triaging E2E test failures from CI run ${RUN_ID}.\\n             Follow the /e2e-triage skill instructions in .claude/skills/e2e-triage/SKILL.md.\\n             Artifact directory: ${ARTIFACT_DIR}\\n             CI run URL: ${{ github.event.workflow_run.html_url }}\\n             Do NOT ask questions — act autonomously.\\n             For flaky fixes: create a PR.\\n             For real bugs: create or comment on GitHub issues.\\n             Print a summary table at the end.\\\"\\n```\\n\\n### Key Design Choices\\n\\n- **`--model claude-opus-4-6`** — Opus for best analysis quality (per user preference)\\n- **`--allowedTools`** — Explicitly whitelists safe tools; prevents Claude from running arbitrary commands. `Bash(mise run *)` allows test/lint/fmt, `Bash(gh *)` allows issue/PR creation, `Bash(git *)` allows branch/commit operations.\\n- **`permissions`** — Workflow needs `contents: write` (push branches), `pull-requests: write` (create PRs), `issues: write` (create/comment issues), `actions: read` (download artifacts from triggering run)\\n- **`timeout-minutes: 30`** — Generous limit for Opus to analyze multiple failures\\n- **`GH_TOKEN`** — Uses `GITHUB_TOKEN` (auto-provided) for `gh` CLI operations within the repo\\n- **No Slack notification** — The existing `e2e.yml` already notifies Slack on failure. The triage workflow creates PRs/issues which generate their own GitHub notifications.\\n\\n### Artifact Download in `workflow_run` Context\\n\\nThe `workflow_run` event provides `github.event.workflow_run.id` which is the run ID of the triggering E2E workflow. The download script uses this to fetch artifacts via `gh run download`. The `actions: read` permission on the triage workflow allows downloading artifacts from the triggering run.\\n\\n### Safety Guards\\n\\n- **Only runs on failure** — `if: github.event.workflow_run.conclusion == 'failure'`\\n- **Only on main** — The E2E workflow only runs on `push: main` and `workflow_dispatch`, so triage only triggers for main branch failures\\n- **Tool allowlist** — Claude cannot run arbitrary bash commands\\n- **Timeout** — 30 minute hard limit prevents runaway costs\\n- **Concurrency** — Consider adding concurrency group to prevent parallel triage runs:\\n  ```yaml\\n  concurrency:\\n    group: e2e-triage\\n    cancel-in-progress: true\\n  ```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Files to Modify\\n\\n| File | Action | Purpose |\\n|------|--------|---------|\\n| `scripts/download-e2e-artifacts.sh` | **Create** | Artifact download script |\\n| `.claude/skills/e2e-triage/SKILL.md` | **Create** | Triage skill definition |\\n| `.github/workflows/e2e-triage.yml` | **Create** | CI workflow: auto-triage on E2E failure |\\n| `e2e/README.md` | **Edit** | Add triage skill + CI workflow reference |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Verification\\n\\n1. **Script test:** Run `scripts/download-e2e-artifacts.sh latest` and verify artifacts download correctly with proper directory structure\\n2. **Local mode test:** Point `/e2e-triage` at an existing local artifact path (from `e2e/artifacts/`) and verify analysis works without `gh`\\n3. **Canary check:** After any flaky fixes, `mise run test:e2e:canary` must pass\\n4. **Lint:** `mise run fmt && mise run lint` on any modified Go test files\\n5. **CI workflow validation:** Check workflow syntax with `actionlint .github/workflows/e2e-triage.yml` or push to a branch and verify it parses correctly in GitHub Actions UI\\n6. **End-to-end:** After merging, trigger a manual E2E run (`workflow_dispatch`) for a known-flaky agent, let it fail, and verify the triage workflow fires and produces a PR or issue\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Design Decisions\\n\\n- **`claude -p` with `workflow_run`** — Full Claude Code capabilities in CI; intelligent analysis, not regex-based\\n- **Opus model** — Best quality for nuanced root cause analysis; ~$15/run but only runs on failures\\n- **Batched PR** for all flaky fixes from one run — fewer PRs to review\\n- **Issue dedup** — search existing open issues before creating; add verification comment if found\\n- **Skill embeds debug-e2e methodology** rather than \\\"calling\\\" it — skills are instructions, not callable functions. Self-contained is more reliable.\\n- **Script is separate** from skill — reusable by humans (`scripts/download-e2e-artifacts.sh latest`) without invoking Claude\\n- **Local mode supported** — accepts local artifact paths to debug without `gh` CLI\\n- **Tool allowlist in CI** — prevents Claude from running arbitrary commands; only `mise`, `gh`, `git`, and file operations\\n\\n\\nIf you need specific details from before exiting plan mode (like exact code snippets, error messages, or content you generated), read the full transcript at: /Users/alisha/.claude/projects/-Users-alisha-Projects-devenv-cli/eefc0e02-c46e-41bd-a002-b0f50ef793dd.jsonl\"},\"uuid\":\"b17c9fc3-9487-4c4a-aaf8-c7215abc08d0\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T19:38:12.483Z\",\"planContent\":\"# E2E Triage Automation — Implementation Plan\\n\\n## Context\\n\\nE2E tests on `main` are flaky and constantly changing. When they fail in CI, someone has to manually download artifacts, analyze them, figure out if it's a real bug or agent non-determinism, and then either fix the test or file a bug. This plan automates that entire workflow with a new `/e2e-triage` skill backed by a reusable artifact download script.\\n\\n**Outcome**: E2E failures on `main` auto-trigger Claude Code (Opus) in CI via `workflow_run`. Claude downloads artifacts, analyzes failures, classifies flaky vs real bug, and creates a batched PR (flaky) or GitHub issue with dedup (real bug). Also available locally via `/e2e-triage`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## New Files\\n\\n### 1. `scripts/download-e2e-artifacts.sh`\\n\\nReusable shell script for downloading E2E artifacts from GitHub Actions.\\n\\n**Interface:**\\n```\\nUsage: scripts/download-e2e-artifacts.sh [RUN_ID | RUN_URL | \\\"latest\\\"]\\n  - RUN_ID:  numeric GitHub Actions run ID\\n  - RUN_URL: full URL like https://github.com/entireio/cli/actions/runs/12345\\n  - \\\"latest\\\": most recent failed E2E run on main\\n```\\n\\n**Behavior:**\\n- Requires `gh` CLI installed and authenticated (validates upfront)\\n- For `latest